hs|ss|nt|Vanderbilt became declarer in 6@S after the above auction. We are not sure what most of the bids mean, but Vanderbilt was a pioneer of the strong 1@C system. We suspect that 1@C was an artificial strong bid, 1@D was an artificial negative response (in terms of high cards), and 2NT was an artificial force. We think that the rest of the auction was natural.|pg||
ls|ss|pc|D4|nt|West's opening lead was a small diamond and Vanderbilt's partner (whose name was not mentioned in the article in ^*BThe Bridge World^*N) put down a very strong hand as dummy. Unfortunately the strong hand in dummy did not fit Vanderbilt's hand very well and the contract was far from laydown. Think about how you would play this deal as declarer before reading on.|pg||sk||hs|es|hs|ws|nt|Vanderbilt decided that the contract would be unlikely to make if the trump suit broke 4-1. He therefore assumed that trumps were 3-2 |pg||ls|es|ls|ws|hs|nc|hs|sc|hs|ss|at|and played to maximize his chances of establishing dummy's club suit under that assumption. |pg||ls|nc|ls|sc|ls|ss|hs|ec|hs|es|at|^*BThe Bridge World^*N did not report the exact East-West hands, but the article stated that East was dealt 3 spades to the @SJ and 4 clubs to the @CQ.|pg||ls|ec|ls|es|hs|nd|hs|sc|nt|Vanderbilt's key play came at trick 1 when he won West's diamond opening lead in dummy and discarded the singleton club from the closed hand. |pg||

